    <div class="reading-time-badge">⏱️ ~45 min read</div>
    <div class="meta">
      <strong>Created for:</strong> Waseem (English Teacher & Coder)<br />
      <strong>Level:</strong> Intermediate (After completing Level 1)<br />
      <strong>Date:</strong> February 2026<br />
      <strong>Topics:</strong> robots.txt, HTTP Status Codes, XML Sitemaps, Core Web Vitals, Speed Optimization
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- Table of Contents -->
  <SidebarTOC sections={sections} />

  <!-- Introduction to Technical SEO -->
  <section id="intro">
    <h2>🚀 Introduction to Technical SEO</h2>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>📚 Remember Level 1?</h4>
      <p>We learned about content (titles, headings, alt text, schema).</p>
      <p><strong>Level 2 is different:</strong> We're learning about <em>infrastructure</em> — how bots access, crawl, and understand your site.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Why Technical SEO Matters for Coders</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Skill</th>
          <th>Marketer</th>
          <th>Coder (You)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Write good content</td>
          <td>✅</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Fix robots.txt</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Create XML sitemaps</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Debug 404 errors</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Optimize Core Web Vitals</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Set up 301 redirects</td>
          <td>❌</td>
          <td>✅</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="success-box">
      <h4>💡 Your Advantage</h4>
      <p>Companies hire coders for Technical SEO because marketers <em>cannot</em> edit server configurations, fix HTTP headers, or optimize code performance. This is YOUR domain!</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic 1: robots.txt -->
  <section id="robots">
    <h2>🛡️ Topic 1: The Security Guard (robots.txt)</h2>

    <h3>What is robots.txt?</h3>
    <p>Imagine your website is a <strong>house</strong>. You want Google to visit most rooms, but maybe there's a <strong>private room</strong> (like an admin panel or test page) you don't want Google to see.</p>

    <p>The <code>robots.txt</code> file is your <strong>security guard</strong> at the front gate, telling bots where they can and cannot go.</p>

    <h3>Where It Lives</h3>
    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>📍 Location</h4>
      <p><code>https://yoursite.com/robots.txt</code></p>
      <p>It MUST be at the root of your domain. If it's in a subfolder, Google won't find it!</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Basic Syntax</h3>
    <pre><code>User-agent: *
Disallow: /admin/
Disallow: /private-page.html
Allow: /</code></pre>

    <h3>What This Means</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Directive</th>
          <th>Meaning</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>User-agent: *</code></td>
          <td>These rules apply to <strong>all bots</strong> (Google, Bing, AI crawlers)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Disallow: /admin/</code></td>
          <td><strong>Do NOT visit</strong> anything in the /admin/ folder</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>Allow: /</code></td>
          <td><strong>You CAN visit</strong> everything else</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Real-World Example: Google's robots.txt</h3>
    <p>Visit <a href="https://www.google.com/robots.txt" target="_blank">google.com/robots.txt</a> to see how Google blocks its own pages!</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <h4>⚠️ Important</h4>
      <p><code>robots.txt</code> tells bots where NOT to go. It does NOT delete pages from search results. If other sites link to your blocked page, it might still appear in Google (just without a description).</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question-box">
      <h4>🤔 Socratic Question 1</h4>
      <p>You want <strong>only Google</strong> to visit your site, but block all other bots (Bing, AI crawlers, etc.). How would you change this line?</p>
      <pre><code>User-agent: *</code></pre>
      <p><strong>Think about it:</strong> What should replace the <code>*</code>?</p>
      <div class="tip-box">
        <h4>✅ Answer</h4>
        <p><code>User-agent: Googlebot</code></p>
        <p>This tells ONLY Google's bot to follow these rules. Other bots will ignore them.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="question-box">
      <h4>🤔 Socratic Question 2</h4>
      <p>You run a restaurant website with these pages:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><code>/menu</code> - Public menu ✅</li>
        <li><code>/admin/login</code> - Admin login 🔐</li>
        <li><code>/test-page</code> - Unfinished page 🚧</li>
        <li><code>/user/profile</code> - Customer profiles 👤</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Which would you put in <code>Disallow</code>?</strong></p>
      <div class="tip-box">
        <h4>✅ Answer</h4>
        <pre><code>Disallow: /admin/
Disallow: /test-page
Disallow: /user/profile</code></pre>
        <p><em>Keep /menu open so Google can index it!</em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic 2: XML Sitemaps -->
  <section id="sitemap">
    <h2>🗺️ Topic 2: The Table of Contents (XML Sitemaps)</h2>

    <h3>🧠 What Is an XML Sitemap?</h3>
    <p>Think of an XML sitemap as a <strong>table of contents</strong> for search engines. It's a file that lists all your important pages so Google doesn't miss any when crawling your site.</p>

    <p>Here's the key idea: <code>robots.txt</code> tells bots what <strong>NOT</strong> to crawl (the "don't" list), while your <strong>XML sitemap</strong> tells them what <strong>TO</strong> crawl (the "do" list). They work together like a map and a "no entry" sign.</p>

    <p>Why does this matter? When you add a new page to your site, Google might not find it immediately—especially if it's buried deep in your navigation. A sitemap gives Google a <strong>direct line</strong> to all your important content.</p>

    <div class="reflect-box">
      <h4>🤔 Reflection #1</h4>
      <p>If you add a new page to your site, why might it not appear in search immediately? How could a sitemap help?</p>
    </div>

    <div class="reflect-box">
      <h4>🤔 Reflection #2</h4>
      <p>Look at your project's folder structure. Which pages are "important" enough to list in a sitemap? Why would you exclude some pages?</p>
    </div>

    <h3>💻 Code Example: Minimal sitemap.xml</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?&gt;
&lt;urlset xmlns="http://www.sitemaps.org/schemas/sitemap/0.9"&gt;
    &lt;!-- Your homepage --&gt;
    &lt;url&gt;
        &lt;loc&gt;https://mysite.com/&lt;/loc&gt;
        &lt;lastmod&gt;2026-02-28&lt;/lastmod&gt;
        &lt;priority&gt;1.0&lt;/priority&gt;
    &lt;/url&gt;

    &lt;!-- Your about page --&gt;
    &lt;url&gt;
        &lt;loc&gt;https://mysite.com/about.html&lt;/loc&gt;
        &lt;lastmod&gt;2026-02-15&lt;/lastmod&gt;
        &lt;priority&gt;0.8&lt;/priority&gt;
    &lt;/url&gt;

    &lt;!-- Your blog post --&gt;
    &lt;url&gt;
        &lt;loc&gt;https://mysite.com/blog/seo-guide.html&lt;/loc&gt;
        &lt;lastmod&gt;2026-02-20&lt;/lastmod&gt;
        &lt;priority&gt;0.6&lt;/priority&gt;
    &lt;/url&gt;
&lt;/urlset&gt;</code></pre>

    <h3>Understanding the Tags</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Tag</th>
          <th>What It Means</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;loc&gt;</code></td>
          <td>The full URL of the page</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;lastmod&gt;</code></td>
          <td>When you last updated this page (helps Google know if it's fresh)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><code>&lt;priority&gt;</code></td>
          <td>Importance (0.0 to 1.0). 1.0 = most important (usually homepage)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>💡 Where does it go?</h4>
      <p>Place your sitemap at: <code>https://yoursite.com/sitemap.xml</code></p>
      <p><strong>Pro tip:</strong> After creating your sitemap, submit it to Google Search Console so Google knows it exists!</p>
    </div>

    <div class="key-takeaway-box">
      <h4>🎯 Key Takeaway</h4>
      <p>Your robots.txt says "stay out of these rooms" while your sitemap says "here are all the important rooms to visit." Use both for complete crawl control.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="question-box">
      <h4>🤔 Socratic Question 3</h4>
      <p>You have a website with 100 pages. Which ones should go in your sitemap?</p>
      <div class="tip-box">
        <h4>✅ Answer</h4>
        <p>Focus on pages that <strong>bring value</strong> to users:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>✅ Product pages, blog posts, services (content people search for)</li>
          <li>✅ Important category pages</li>
          <li>❌ Admin pages, login forms, thank-you pages (no search value)</li>
          <li>❌ Duplicate content or filtered search results</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic 3: HTTP Status Codes -->
  <section id="status">
    <h2>📞 Topic 3: The Bot's Language (HTTP Status Codes)</h2>

    <h3>What Are Status Codes?</h3>
    <p>When Googlebot requests a page, your server responds with a <strong>3-digit code</strong>. Think of these like <strong>phone call statuses</strong>:</p>

    <h3>The 4 Most Important Codes</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Code</th>
          <th>Name</th>
          <th>Meaning</th>
          <th>Analogy</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>200</strong></td>
          <td>✅ OK</td>
          <td>Page loaded successfully</td>
          <td>📞 "Hello, I'm here!"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>301</strong></td>
          <td>🔄 Moved Permanently</td>
          <td>Page moved to new URL</td>
          <td>📞 "I moved! Update your address book."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>404</strong></td>
          <td>❌ Not Found</td>
          <td>Page doesn't exist</td>
          <td>📞 "Wrong number. Nobody lives here."</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>500</strong></td>
          <td>🔌 Server Error</td>
          <td>Server crashed/broken</td>
          <td>📞 "Phone line is dead. Try later."</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>How to Check Status Codes</h3>
    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>💡 Browser DevTools</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Open Chrome DevTools (F12)</li>
        <li>Go to Network tab</li>
        <li>Reload the page</li>
        <li>Click the first request - you'll see the status code</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <h4>⚠️ Common Mistake: Soft 404s</h4>
      <p>A "soft 404" is when a page returns 200 OK but shows "Page not found" content. Google hates this because it wastes crawl budget!</p>
      <pre><code>&lt;!-- ❌ BAD: Soft 404 --&gt;
&lt;!-- Server returns 200, but content says "Not Found" --&gt;

&lt;!-- ✅ GOOD: Proper 404 --&gt;
&lt;!-- Server returns 404 status code --&gt;</code></pre>
    </div>

    <h3>301 Redirects: When You Move Pages</h3>
    <p>When you delete or move a page, use a <strong>301 redirect</strong> to tell Google where the content went.</p>

    <pre><code>&lt;!-- .htaccess example --&gt;
Redirect 301 /old-page.html https://mysite.com/new-page.html</code></pre>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h4>🔧 Why 301 Matters</h4>
      <p>With a 301 redirect, Google transfers <strong>90-99% of the ranking power</strong> from the old page to the new page. Without it, you lose all your SEO!</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic 4: Speed & Performance -->
  <section id="speed">
    <h2>⚡ Topic 4: Speed & Performance Basics</h2>

    <h3>Why Speed Matters</h3>
    <p>Google uses page speed as a <strong>ranking factor</strong>. Faster pages rank higher. It's that simple.</p>

    <div class="success-box">
      <h4>✅ The Speed Stats</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>1-second delay = <strong>7% reduction in conversions</strong></li>
        <li>3-second delay = <strong>32% increase in bounce rate</strong></li>
        <li>53% of mobile users leave if page takes >3 seconds to load</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Speed Basics for Coders</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Technique</th>
          <th>Impact</th>
          <th>Your Role</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Image Optimization</td>
          <td>High (images are 50%+ of page size)</td>
          <td>Compress, use WebP, lazy load</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Minification</td>
          <td>Medium (10-20% reduction)</td>
          <td>Remove whitespace, comments</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>CDN</td>
          <td>High for global audiences</td>
          <td>Use Cloudflare, AWS CloudFront</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Caching</td>
          <td>High for returning visitors</td>
          <td>Set cache headers, use service workers</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Image Optimization Example</h3>
    <pre><code>&lt;!-- ❌ BAD: Large uncompressed image --&gt;
&lt;img src="huge-photo.jpg" alt="Photo"&gt;

&lt;!-- ✅ GOOD: Compressed, WebP format --&gt;
&lt;img src="photo.webp" alt="Photo" width="800" height="600" loading="lazy"&gt;</code></pre>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>💡 Pro Tip</h4>
      <p>Always specify <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> attributes. This prevents <strong>layout shift</strong> (CLS), which we'll cover next.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Topic 5: Core Web Vitals -->
  <section id="core-web-vitals">
    <h2>📊 Topic 5: Core Web Vitals Metrics</h2>

    <h3>What Are Core Web Vitals?</h3>
    <p>Core Web Vitals are the <strong>three speed metrics</strong> Google measures for every page. They're part of Google's ranking algorithm.</p>

    <h3>The Three Metrics</h3>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Metric</th>
          <th>Measures</th>
          <th>Good Target</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>LCP</strong><br> Largest Contentful Paint</td>
          <td>How fast the main content loads</td>
          <td>&lt; 2.5 seconds</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>FID</strong><br> First Input Delay</td>
          <td>How fast the page responds to clicks</td>
          <td>&lt; 100 milliseconds</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>CLS</strong><br> Cumulative Layout Shift</td>
          <td>How much the page jumps around while loading</td>
          <td>&lt; 0.1</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>LCP: Largest Contentful Paint</h3>
    <p><strong>Question:</strong> What is the largest element on the page?</p>
    <p>Usually: Hero image, big heading, or featured video.</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ How to Improve LCP</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Optimize and compress images</li>
        <li>Use modern formats (WebP, AVIF)</li>
        <li>Preload important resources: <code>&lt;link rel="preload" href="hero.jpg" as="image"&gt;</code></li>
        <li>Remove render-blocking JavaScript</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>FID: First Input Delay</h3>
    <p><strong>Question:</strong> How long does the page freeze when a user clicks?</p>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ How to Improve FID</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Split long JavaScript tasks into smaller chunks</li>
        <li>Remove unused JavaScript</li>
        <li>Defer non-critical JavaScript: <code>&lt;script defer src="..."&gt;</code></li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>CLS: Cumulative Layout Shift</h3>
    <p><strong>Question:</strong> How much does content jump around as the page loads?</p>

    <div class="warning-box">
      <h4>⚠️ CLS Example</h4>
      <p>User goes to click a button, but suddenly an ad loads above it and the button moves down. User clicks the ad by accident. <strong>This is CLS.</strong></p>
    </div>

    <div class="tip-box">
      <h4>✅ How to Improve CLS</h4>
      <ul>
        <li>Always include <code>width</code> and <code>height</code> on images</li>
        <li>Reserve space for ads: <code>min-height: 250px;</code></li>
        <li>Don't insert content above existing content unless responding to user interaction</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h3>Testing Your Core Web Vitals</h3>
    <div class="success-box">
      <h4>🛠️ Tools to Use</h4>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>PageSpeed Insights:</strong> <a href="https://pagespeed.web.dev" target="_blank">pagespeed.web.dev</a></li>
        <li><strong>Chrome DevTools:</strong> Lighthouse tab (F12 → Lighthouse)</li>
        <li><strong>Search Console:</strong> Core Web Vitals report</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Deep Dive Questions -->
  <section id="deep-dive">
    <h2>🤔 Deep Dive Questions</h2>

    <div class="question-box">
      <h4>Deep Dive Question 1</h4>
      <p>Look at this robots.txt:</p>
      <pre><code>User-agent: *
Disallow: /admin/
Disallow: /temp/
Disallow: /search?q=
Allow: /</code></pre>
      <p><strong>Can Google visit these URLs?</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li><code>/about.html</code> → ?</li>
        <li><code>/admin/dashboard.html</code> → ?</li>
        <li><code>/search?q=cake</code> → ?</li>
        <li><code>/temp/test.html</code> → ?</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="tip-box">
        <h4>✅ Answers</h4>
        <p>1. ✅ Yes (not blocked)<br>
        2. ❌ No (/admin/ is blocked)<br>
        3. ❌ No (/search?q= is blocked)<br>
        4. ❌ No (/temp/ is blocked)</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="question-box">
      <h4>Deep Dive Question 2</h4>
      <p><strong>Why does Google block so many of its own pages in robots.txt?</strong></p>
      <p>Think about these reasons:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>🔐 <strong>Private:</strong> User preferences, settings</li>
        <li>🔄 <strong>Duplicate:</strong> Multiple language versions</li>
        <li>🚧 <strong>Not Ready:</strong> Test pages, development</li>
        <li>♾️ <strong>Infinite Loops:</strong> Search results linking to search results</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quiz Section -->
  <section id="quiz" class="quiz-section">
    <h2>🎯 Final Knowledge Test</h2>
    <p>Test your understanding of Technical SEO!</p>

    <form id="quiz" class="quiz-form">
      <div class="question" data-question="1">
        <p><strong>1. What is robots.txt?</strong></p>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="a"> a) A sitemap for search engines</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="b"> b) A file that tells bots which pages to crawl</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="c"> c) A redirect rule</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="2">
        <p><strong>2. What does a 200 status code mean?</strong></p>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="a"> a) Page not found</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="b"> b) Page moved permanently</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="c"> c) Page loaded successfully</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="3">
        <p><strong>3. What is an XML sitemap?</strong></p>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="a"> a) A list of all pages on your site</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="b"> b) A site design template</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q3" value="c"> c) A database file</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="4">
        <p><strong>4. What does LCP measure?</strong></p>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="a"> a) How fast the page responds to clicks</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="b"> b) How fast the main content loads</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q4" value="c"> c) How much the page shifts</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="5">
        <p><strong>5. What is a 301 redirect?</strong></p>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="a"> a) Temporary redirect</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="b"> b) Permanent redirect</label>
        <label><input type="radio" name="q5" value="c"> c) Error page</label>
      </div>

      <div class="question" data-question="6">
